          >
            Check Price on Amazon &rarr;
          </a>
        </div>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros">
            <h4>What We Like</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Massive 1-inch sensor = great low light quality</li>
              <li>Mechanical gimbal is smoother than GoPro HyperSmooth</li>
              <li>Fastest startup: Flip screen, shoot in 2 seconds</li>
              <li>Face tracking is incredibly sticky</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons">
            <h4>Trade-offs</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Not rugged or waterproof (needs a case)</li>
              <li>Built-in mic is good, but external mic is better for wind</li>
              <li>Fixed lens aperture means you need ND filters</li>
              <li>Non-removable battery limits all-day shooting</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>Detailed Performance</h2>
      <div class="grid">
        <article class="card card-plain">
          <h3>Image Quality</h3>
          <p>
            The jump to a 1-inch sensor is massive. Night footage that would be
            mush on a phone or GoPro looks clean and professional here. Skin
            tones are natural and pleasing straight out of camera.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="card card-plain">
          <h3>Vertical Workflows</h3>
          <p>
            The rotating screen isn't just a gimmick. It physically rotates the
            UI and changes aspect ratio, making it the fastest way to switch
            between YouTube (16:9) and TikTok (9:16) shooting.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="card card-plain">
          <h3>Sound</h3>
          <p>
            Pair it with the DJI Mic 2 (which connects wirelessly without a
            receiver!) and you have a pro-level interview setup that fits in a
            jacket pocket.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section" id="affiliate">
      <h2>Affiliate Disclosure</h2>
      <p class="section-sub">
        We buy our own gear or rent it. No manufacturers paid for this review.
        We earn a commission if you use our links, which keeps this site
        ad-free.
      </p>
    </section>
    <!-- FAQ Section -->
    <section class="section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="faq-container">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>
            <button class="faq-toggle" aria-expanded="false">
              <span class="faq-icon"></span>
              Is the Pocket 3 enough to replace my vlog camera?
            </button>
          </h3>
          <div class="faq-answer" style="max-height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
            <p>
              For 80% of vloggers, yes. The gimbal stabilization is unbeatable,
              and the 1-inch sensor handles low light well. You lose some
              creative control (no interchangeable lenses, fixed aperture), but
              the convenience and footage quality are incredible. Keep a backup
              camera for specialty shots.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>
            <button class="faq-toggle" aria-expanded="false">
              <span class="faq-icon"></span>
              How long does the battery last?
            </button>
          </h3>
          <div class="faq-answer" style="max-height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
            <p>
              About 2 hours of continuous 4K30 recording. The battery is
              non-removable, so bring a USB-C power bank for all-day shooting.
              DJI sells a battery handle accessory that extends runtime to 4-5
              hours. Fast charging via USB-C gives you 50% in 15 minutes.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>
            <button class="faq-toggle" aria-expanded="false">
              <span class="faq-icon"></span>
              Does it work well in low light?
            </button>
          </h3>
          <div class="faq-answer" style="max-height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
            <p>
              Better than any action camera or phone, but not as good as
              full-frame cameras. The 1-inch sensor performs well up to ISO
              3200. You'll see noise in dim restaurants or nighttime streets,
              but it's totally usable. The ActiveTrack works even in low light,
              which is impressive.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>
            <button class="faq-toggle" aria-expanded="false">
              <span class="faq-icon"></span>
              Can I use it for professional work?
            </button>
          </h3>
          <div class="faq-answer" style="max-height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
            <p>
              Many professionals use it as a B-camera for BTS
              (behind-the-scenes), quick social media content, or gimbal shots.
              The 10-bit D-Log M gives you good color grading flexibility. It
              won't replace an A7 IV for client work, but it's an excellent
              secondary tool that fits in your pocket.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>
            <button class="faq-toggle" aria-expanded="false">
              <span class="faq-icon"></span>
              What accessories are essential?
            </button>
          </h3>
          <div class="faq-answer" style="max-height: 0; overflow: hidden;">
            <p>
              Get the DJI Mic 2 for wireless audioâ€”it integrates seamlessly. The
              wide-angle lens attachment adds creative options. A wrist strap is
              a must (the Pocket 3 is slippery). Consider the waterproof case if
              you shoot near water. Skip the ND filters unless you shoot in
              bright sunshine often.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

